text: Your Tuesday Evening BriefingHere’s what you need to know at the end of the day.
The Book Review PodcastDavid Sedaris talks about his new book and life as an essayist.
Listen to ‘The Daily’Trump shut the door on migrants. Will Biden open it?
The House passed a $741 billion defense bill with a veto-proof majority, setting up a potential showdown with President Trump.

The Oxford-AstraZeneca effort held great promise to help arrest the pandemic. But a series of miscues caused it to fall behind in the U.S.A pattern of communication failures have damaged the company’s relationship with regulators and, in at least one instance, slowed the vaccine’s development.
A 90-year-old former jewelry shop assistant was the first to get a shot, followed, appropriately enough, by a man named William Shakespeare.
The F.D.A. found that Pfizer’s vaccine worked well regardless of a volunteer’s race, weight or age.

Supreme Court Rejects Republican Request to Overturn Pennsylvania ResultsIn a one-sentence order, the court rejected a Republican request to challenge election results that had already been certified and submitted.
After Trump’s Loss in Arizona, State Republicans Turn on One AnotherA top Republican told the governor to “shut the hell up.” Another official described a lawmaker as a resident of “Crazytown.”
Biden’s Pentagon Pick Reignites Debate Over Civilian Control of MilitaryCongress would need to approve a waiver for Gen. Lloyd Austin, a recently retired general, to serve in the civilian post.

Michèle Flournoy Again Finds Her Shot at the Top Pentagon Job ElusivePresident-elect Joe Biden’s decision to nominate retired Gen. Lloyd Austin III enraged many of the women Ms. Flournoy had elevated.
An investigation into the culture at Fort Hood, a major military base in Texas, came in response to the killing of a specialist who had reported harassment.
The Silicon Valley company said hackers — almost certainly Russian — made off with tools that could be used to mount new attacks around the world.

Shift to a Not-So-Frozen North Is Well Underway, Scientists Warn“There is no reason to think that in 30 years much of anything will be as it is today,” one of the editors of a new report on the Arctic climate said.

President Barack Obama on a visit to Midway Atoll in 2016. Literature is more important than ever, he says. “We need to explain to each other who we are and where we’re going.” A.J. Chavar/The New York Times
